etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Quarterly Journal of the Chemical Society. From phenet- + -idine, after French phénétidine

definitions: Each of three isomeric oily liquid amines having the formula (C₂ H₅ O)C₆ H₄ NH₂, which are ortho-, meta-, and para- amino derivatives of phenetole and are used in the manufacture of dyes.
